               <desc type="site-data">
Lingyin Temple sits at the foot of Mountain Lingyin right next to the West Lake in the northwest of Hangzhou. Its name takes from the meaning of “the location of retreat for immortals”. It is one of the most prominent Buddhist temples in the Jiangnan region throughout its history. According to textual sources of Qing Dynasty, the temple was founded by an Indian monk named Huili in Chinese that can be traced back to 326 AD in East Jin Dynasty. The famous legend of Huili and his monkey may have significantly influenced the emergence of the supernatural monkey hero Sun Wukong 孙悟空 in the folklore novel Xiyouji 西游记 (Journey to the West).
The destiny of Lingyin temple is closely associated with the shift of attitudes towards Buddhism in the imperial courts in different dynasties. In the Northern and Souther dynasties and the subsequent Sui periods, the emperors continued to patronize the development of the monastery, adding new structures and attracting more monks residing in the temple. In Tang Dynasty, the main structures of the temple was heavily destroyed in the Huichang Fanan 会昌法难. However, Lingyin temple came to its peak under the ruling of Yuezhongyi King of Wuyue Kingdom with new constructions of nine multi-storied buildings and 18 pavilions.
               </desc>
